I changed the code around to use a named parameter.

@yetibrain re: using DateTime, unfortunately it has to be a constant expression in an attribute so had to stick w/ string representation

re: your other concern, I'm not sure I totally am following but seems like it would require quite a lot more moving parts and framework changes.  To me, the IgnoreAttribute already acts as test execution metadata leaving the test itself to do it's thing.  This is just 1 addition facet to that metadata.

@aochsner 
You're right, i forgot about the fact that we need constant expressions for attribute params.

As long as the test does never start to execute itself, it needs a caller to execute it. It's the callers responsability to execute a test or not and when. Regarding the IgnoreUntilAttribute it is the easiest way to add it as metadata to the test itself, that's right. But once the IgnoreUntilDate is in the past, it has the same effect to the executor of the test as if it was absent. We can sure classify such test as "previously been ignored" as well as "failed or passed" (the latter because if it is no more ignored it must get executed for sure) but the developer of the test would sure one day delete the entire attribute because the test never travels "back to the future".
